article.headline: Sprewell hits six 3-pointers
article.linkText: Garnett and Sprewell shine in Wolves' win
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Though Kevin Garnett remains their unquestioned leader, the Minnesota Timberwolves derive much of their energy from Latrell Sprewell. He supplied plenty on Wednesday night. Sprewell scored 27 points, including six 3-pointers, to help Minnesota hold off Seattle 90-83. "He's a great barometer," Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said. "Offensively and defensively, the team seems to take his personality a lot." Garnett had 27 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists for Minnesota, which maintained its tenuous lead over San Antonio in the Midwest Division and remained in the hunt for the top seed in the Western Conference playoffs. "We're not playing a team -- we're playing ourselves, so to speak," Sprewell said. "We've got to go out, play hard and try to get wins ... We know what the situation is." The Timberwolves (52-24), who lead the Spurs by 1{ games and trail the Sacramento Kings by one game in the West race, set a franchise record for regular-season victories. Having won six of eight and three in a row, Minnesota appears close to being cured of its recent struggles. Sprewell, by no coincidence, has been playing better lately, too. "Every game, I'm just telling him to be aggressive," Garnett said. "I feel like I need to keep on doing that. ... It sort of makes everybody else aggressive, too." Vitaly Potapenko had 18 points and nine rebounds and Rashard Lewis had 17 points for Seattle. Despite losing valuable reserve Vladimir Radmanovic to a sprained right ankle in the second quarter, the SuperSonics led briefly in the third and frustrated the Timberwolves by staying close the rest of the way. "If we have to find the competitive kindling to get the fire going, that's what we have to do," Sonics guard Brent Barry said. "We have to come out and compete hard against teams that are going somewhere." Sprewell, who posted his highest scoring total in 12 games since getting 31 on March 9 at Seattle, put Minnesota up 82-74 on a 3-pointer with 2:44 left. Lewis cut the lead to 84-79 on a 3-pointer with 1:11 remaining, but Sprewell answered with another 3 to put the game safely away. "We're not on the schedule anymore, so if he gets into a slump, he might be in it for a long time," Barry joked. "If he has anything to do with it, we might play them eight times next year." After scoring 119 points in a five-point loss at Denver the night before, the Sonics ended an awfully streaky month. They began March with six losses in a row, won seven straight and then closed with three consecutive defeats. Seattle (34-41) saw its improbable playoff hopes take another hit, with only seven games left and no chance of finishing with a winning record. The Sonics seemed to match the Wolves' energy, though, which undoubtedly led to some of the second-half frustration on the Minnesota bench. Garnett, peeved at Potapenko for fouling him in the third quarter, faked like he was going to dunk the ball on Potapenko's head and both players picked up technicals after exchanging glares. Cassell and Michael Olowokandi also snipped at each other on the bench during a timeout in the third. "I thought we scrapped," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "The second half -- I liked the fact that there was some fight. We took better care of the ball, and we tried to make a run." Garnett put the Wolves up 65-54 later in that period with the play of the game. Facing the wrong direction, he tossed a shot over his shoulder while being fouled by Potapenko. The ball bounced off the top of the backboard and fell in. A dunk by Allen pulled Seattle within 25-24 early in the second period, but then the Sonics went 5{ minutes without a basket and fell behind by 12. Radmanovic was injured during that span, during which the Wolves scored 11 straight.

Game notes
McMillan had no further update on Radmanovic, who lay on the court in pain during two possession changes until a dead ball allowed Seattle to sub for him. ... Garnett reached the 20-point mark for the 62nd time this season -- breaking the franchise record shared previously by him and Tony Campbell. ... Sonics backup C Jerome James, who was placed on the injured list Tuesday, sat out with an abdominal strain. He doesn't have to sit out the required five games, however, because Seattle is carrying only 11 active players.
